WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.583
(upbeat music)

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:13.270
- When you look at the bands,

00:00:13.270 --> 00:00:14.846
that hook on the X3,

00:00:14.846 --> 00:00:17.430
and the ground plate also,

00:00:17.430 --> 00:00:19.260
they're very soft material

00:00:19.260 --> 00:00:23.450
and they're designed to
give you hundreds of pounds.

00:00:23.450 --> 00:00:25.564
When Dr. Shawn Baker does a deadlift,

00:00:25.564 --> 00:00:28.590
he handles over 700 pounds at the top

00:00:28.590 --> 00:00:30.630
because he's a very tall
guy, the taller you are,

00:00:30.630 --> 00:00:33.840
the more stretch there is, he's six, four.

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:37.220
So incredible forces.

00:00:37.220 --> 00:00:39.200
And these are also layered bands.

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:41.610
So sometimes the top layer

00:00:41.610 --> 00:00:44.380
gets some tiny little nicks and scrapes.

00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:47.980
Now obviously if there's
a cut in the band,

00:00:47.980 --> 00:00:52.510
like through multiple layers
or through all the layers,

00:00:52.510 --> 00:00:53.940
then that band should be replaced.

00:00:53.940 --> 00:00:56.620
But what we've noticed is over time,

00:00:56.620 --> 00:01:00.170
some of these bands just
get little nicks and fraze.

00:01:00.170 --> 00:01:02.210
But it really has to do
with the fact that latex

00:01:02.210 --> 00:01:04.430
is a very soft material.

00:01:04.430 --> 00:01:06.760
And it gets little nicks and fraze in it,

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:09.268
but it still performs just fantastic.

00:01:09.268 --> 00:01:11.890
Now coming up on three years,

00:01:11.890 --> 00:01:13.190
I've been using X3

00:01:13.190 --> 00:01:15.440
because I had it earlier
than everybody else.

00:01:16.350 --> 00:01:19.675
You know, I designed it
and then got the prototype.

00:01:19.675 --> 00:01:24.090
So, my first set of bands I still have,

00:01:24.090 --> 00:01:25.730
they don't look pretty,

00:01:25.730 --> 00:01:27.480
but they work perfectly.

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:31.162
So, the analogy I like to use is like,

00:01:31.162 --> 00:01:34.050
a rubber tire on your car.

00:01:34.050 --> 00:01:36.150
You can buy a new car with new tires on it

00:01:36.150 --> 00:01:38.010
and the tires look great
and the car looks great.

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:41.110
You drive up 500 miles,
the car still looks great,

00:01:41.110 --> 00:01:43.495
but the tires they don't look new anymore.

00:01:43.495 --> 00:01:47.280
But they're still gonna
go another 10,000 miles.

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:49.400
So, it doesn't really matter.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:51.440
So, don't worry too much about the bands

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:53.580
unless like I said there's a cut

00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:55.400
that goes all the way through,

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:58.513
or something like that,
that one should be replaced.

00:02:00.220 --> 00:02:02.280
And you know, we have customer service

00:02:02.280 --> 00:02:04.443
for questions beyond that.

